    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Another thing to watch out for is the phrase \"arising out of or occurring in connection with.\" This is a bit of a sneaky clause, as it can be interpreted broadly. It means that the Disclosing Party can claim damages for any losses or damages that are related to the contract, even if they're not directly caused by your actions.\n\nFor example, if you're working on a project and a third-party vendor you hired to do some work for you causes a problem, the Disclosing Party might still try to claim damages from you, even if the vendor is the one who messed up. This can be a bit of a trap, as it can make it difficult to determine who's actually responsible for the damages.\n\nIt's also worth noting that the phrase \"reasonable attorneys' fees\" can be a bit of a slippery slope. What constitutes \"reasonable\" fees can be subjective, and the Disclosing Party might try to claim excessive fees if they can argue that they're necessary to defend against the claim.\n\nAs for hidden risks, it's always a good idea to have a lawyer review the contract and help you understand any potential pitfalls. But in general, it's a good idea to be cautious when you see language like this, as",
